The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 London, Oct. 19 (PTI): A wheelchair-bound Indian-origin woman, suffering from cerebral palsy, will skydive from more than 14,000 feet to raise funds to fight against racism and fascism in the UK.           
	Rupy Kaur, 22, a disability activist, said money raised from the act would go to Searchlight and Hope Not Hate  organisations campaigning against racism and fascism.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): If a person brought before a court claims to be a juvenile (under the age of 18), the court must ascertain his age immediately, Bombay High Court has held in a recent murder case. The Juvenile Justice Board and not an ordinary court tries any person who had been a juvenile at the time of committing the crime.                  
	 Indore (PTI): Twenty-five people were injured, two of them critically, in a post-Diwali ritual on Sunday where revellers throw explosives-filled fruits at each other. Fifteen participants and 10 spectators sustained injuries. Hingot, a jungle fruit, is emptied, filled with explosives and thrown at participants in this ritual.                  
	 Erode (PTI): Two persons drowned while bathing in a river at a village here on Sunday. Chokkalingam, 42, was carried away by the currents of the Bhavani river and his relative, Thangaraj, 39, drowned while trying to save him.                   
	Rameswaram (PTI): Police arrested eight people for trying to smuggle out sea leeches to Sri Lanka. A consignment of leeches, weighing 1,000kg and worth about Rs 15 lakh, was seized. Three other smugglers escaped.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The defence ministry has started collecting dental records of the nearly 15 lakh armed forces personnel for identifying casualties in combat. We are coming up with a centrally monitored database containing the dental records. It will be a digital record, director general, dental services, Lieutenant General S.B. Sehajpal said.
                                                                                                                           
